    First, making an exception to  what most of you are considering general looting guide lines doesn't mean this is how I handle all lotto's. We were up against a time table of getting people together quickly, buffing and killing the turtle before someone attempted a ks. I was not going to randomly do a /who all 50 60 shaman while kiting a 300 quad hitting turtle. I knew the ranger could bring his cousins shaman so I asked him to do so. So by asking him to help out, he very well deserved a chance at a loot item as much as anyone else who particapted.<br>
<br>
    As far as knowing the looting rules before hand, they were stating before the turtle was brought it. This was done in /say and not guildchat. If you didn't pay attention because you were busy talking in tells or afk for a second, it's not my fault. And if you aren't used to raiding with certain people, you should have asked or sent me a /tell asking for the rules to be explained to you. The looting rules were also stated AGAIN at the time of death. Everyone rolled, he won and AND THEN Slinker started wining. Why did you bring it after the lotto was done? Because if you had won, there wouldn't have been a problem. Everyone would have had their fair chance and you would have had your map piece. I also told you I would gladly hear any aruments AFTER the lotto'ing of all items was done. I noticed you departed from our group while lotto'ing the last of the loot ( spells), I attempted a tell which was never recieved-because you LOGGED or went LD. I attempted a second tell mintutes later with the same result. If you had gone LD, you should have sent me a tell saying so and presenting the arugment instead of taking it public. Let's be honest here. Right or wrong, I am telling it how it went and taking the flames for it because people disagree. And that's OK. But at least speak the truth and perhaps try to structure your feelings into something constructive rather then flame after flame.<br>
